sayHello('Bob'); // expected output: Hello, Alice (after 1 second), Hello, Bob (after another second)"

answer:
First, you need to change "function delay(ms) {
    return new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, ms));
}" to "function delay(ms) {
    return new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, ms));
}
", since you're using ES2015 (ECMAScript 6).

Second, you need to change "sayHello(name) {
    await delay(1000);
    console.log('Hello, ' + name);
}" to "sayHello(name) {
    await delay(1000);
    console.log('Hello, ' + name);
}
". Otherwise, the "await" keyword will not work as expected.

Third, you need to change the order of "sayHello('Alice');
sayHello('Bob');" to "sayHello('Alice');
sayHello('Bob');". Otherwise, "sayHello('Alice');" will run first, and "sayHello('Bob');" will run after "sayHello('Alice');" has completed, but you want "sayHello('Bob');" to run after "sayHello('Alice');" has been running for 1 second.

When all these changes are applied, your code should work as expected.

